In the presence of over-dispersion, the Poisson model is replaced by a negative binomial model where the conditional mean remains unchanged but the variance δ is modified to μt(1 + μtψ) with over-dispersion parameter ψ > 0. The extent of over-dispersion is captured by how far the term ψ deviates from zero. An extensive discussion on handling over-dispersion can be found in the work of Ver Hoef and Boveng [21]. We are interested in two different types of viruses transmitted through the same route, i.e. respiratory illness. Let xk, t − 1 denote climatic covariates with τk coefficients in the model and k = 1, … , K covariates. In the model, it is assumed that the cases follow a negative binomial distribution, yt ∣ yt − 1~NegBin(μt, ψ), with conditional mean2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
